Document Title: 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  FBIS Report: Central Eurasia </ABS>
<DATE1>   22 February 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Implications of Supreme Council START I Ratification </TI></H3>
<H4>   Dubious Victory for Kravchuk Seen </H4>
<F P=102> 94WC0030B Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 5 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> 94WC0030B </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Vitaliy Portnikov] </F>
  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk finally managed 
to persuade the Supreme Council to ratify the Strategic 
Offensive Arms Reduction Treaty without any stipulations. 
Ukraine thus became a nonnuclear state, and the president's 
signing of the trilateral American-Russian-Ukrainian agreement 
has been confirmed. Kravchuk is in a sense demonstrating the 
strength of his own positions to his partners at the Moscow 
summit, Boris Yeltsin and Bill Clinton. However, this 
demonstration is almost a Pyrrhic victory. 
  Opting for foreign political concessions, parliamentarians 
decided to "recoup their losses" at the expense of presidential 
power, scheduling elections of the new head of state in June and 
rescinding the power of presidential representative in the 
regions, in which authority is to be returned to the local 
councils. In contrast to representatives of the Russian 
president, who perform only representative functions, 
representatives of the Ukrainian president directly exercise all 
power in the republic's oblasts and cities. And the Ukrainian 
parliament's attempt to deprive Leonid Kravchuk of his needed 
chain of command right at the eve of parliamentary and 
presidential elections distinctly reveals the true measure of 
sympathy the parliamentary corps hold for the head of state. 
  It stands to reason that only the "party of power" can count 
on any serious success in the forthcoming parliamentary 
elections, and that only in the event of this party's victory 
can Leonid Kravchuk hope to have the new parliament call off the 
presidential elections. Or to win such elections. However, there 
is hardly any logical basis for these plans: Voters in 
post-Soviet states have been known to vote the opposition. And 
the last elections in Ukraine (in Crimea) gave the Ukrainian 
leader a good idea of how fickle the sympathies of voters are, 
and how they "love" centrists today. By the way, Leonid Kravchuk 
has been taxed by yet another ordeal--a meeting with the new 
Crimean president, Yuriy Meshkov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-42842 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jpusr016___94020" </HT>


<HEADER>
